Ontological Implications of Languages Without the Verb ‚ÄúTo Be‚Äù
Introduction
Languages such as Arabic and Ancient Egyptian have a notable grammatical feature: they often omit the copula, the verb ‚Äúto be,‚Äù in equating a subject with a predicate (especially in the present tense). For example, where English says ‚ÄúThe student is new,‚Äù Arabic simply says ‚Äúal-·π≠ƒÅlib jadƒ´d‚Äù (‚Äúthe student new‚Äù) opentext.uoregon.edu. In Middle Egyptian, one could say ‚Äúpet jÍú•w‚Äù (‚Äúthe sky blue‚Äù) to mean ‚ÄúThe sky is blue,‚Äù with no separate word for ‚Äúis.‚Äù This contrasts sharply with English (and the Cartesian phrase ‚ÄúI think, therefore I am‚Äù), which relies on an explicit ‚Äúam‚Äù to assert existence. Such differences raise deep questions: How do these copula-free structures encode identity, existence, and thought? And do they imply a fundamentally different ontology ‚Äì perhaps one of assumed or continuous presence, rather than a dualistic being vs. non-being? In exploring these questions, we will examine how Arabic and Ancient Egyptian express identity and agency without ‚Äúto be,‚Äù and consider the philosophical and cognitive ramifications, including links to non-dualism, recursive self-conception, and cultural worldviews in Islamic and Egyptian thought.
Identity and Existence Without an Explicit Copula
In languages lacking an overt ‚Äúto be,‚Äù identity and predication are conveyed by juxtaposition or apposition of nouns/pronouns and their descriptors. In Arabic (a Semitic language), a present-tense nominal sentence pairs a subject with a complement without any verb. For instance, ‚ÄúMuhammad (is) an engineer‚Äù is expressed as ‚ÄúMu·∏•ammad muhandis‚Äù (literally ‚ÄúMuhammad engineer‚Äù) en.wikipedia.org. The copula is implied rather than spoken opentext.uoregon.edu. Only context and grammatical markers (like definiteness) indicate that this is a sentence, not just two nouns. If both subject and predicate are definite (e.g. ‚ÄúMuhammad (is) the engineer‚Äù), Arabic may insert a pronoun (‚ÄúMu·∏•ammad huwa al-muhandis,‚Äù literally ‚ÄúMuhammad he the-engineer‚Äù) as a clarifier en.wikipedia.orgen.wikipedia.org. But notably, there is still no verb ‚Äúto be‚Äù in the present affirmative construction ‚Äì ‚Äúhe‚Äù serves as a dummy linker. In Ancient Egyptian (Middle Egyptian stage), the pattern was similar. A pronoun followed by a noun or adjective constituted a complete identity statement: ‚Äúink s·∫ñ øw‚Äù (literally ‚ÄúI (am) a scribe‚Äù) equated ‚ÄúI‚Äù and ‚Äúscribe‚Äù with no verb. Likewise, descriptions were often given as nominal clauses (noun + adjective), with existence ‚Äúfelt‚Äù rather than stated. Egyptian did have a particle pw that could function as a copular element in certain emphatic sentences (e.g. ‚Äús»ù.j pw‚Äù ‚Äì ‚ÄúHe is my son‚Äù citeseerx.ist.psu.edu), but in most cases the language simply placed elements side by side to denote ‚ÄúX is Y.‚Äù In both Arabic and Egyptian, being is not an action but a default state implicit in naming or describing something.
Crucially, these languages can express existence or being explicitly when necessary ‚Äì but they do so using other means. Arabic has verbs like kƒÅna (‚Äúwas‚Äù) for past existence and laysa (‚Äúis not‚Äù) for negation en.wikipedia.org, as well as terms like mawj≈´d (literally ‚Äúpresent/existing‚Äù) to say ‚Äú(I) exist.‚Äù Ancient Egyptian used verbs meaning ‚Äúto exist‚Äù (wnn) or ‚Äúto become‚Äù (·∏´pr, the root of the name of the transformation god Khepri) in certain contexts universaldependencies.org. However, in ordinary present tense statements of identity or attribute, neither language requires an existence verb. The subject and predicate alone suffice to convey reality. Identity is encoded by direct equivalence (A = B) without a verbal copula as a bridge. In effect, the grammar itself assumes a linkage or unity between subject and predicate. This stands in contrast to English and other Indo-European languages where the copula is obligatory and thus highlights ‚Äúbeing‚Äù as a separate linking relation.
Assumed Being vs. Declared Being: Ontological Shifts
The absence of an explicit ‚Äúto be‚Äù in these languages suggests an ontological stance of assumed existence. If one says ‚ÄúAna mudarris‚Äù (‚ÄúI [am] a teacher‚Äù) in Arabic, the existence of the ‚ÄúI‚Äù as a teacher is taken for granted by simply placing ‚ÄúI‚Äù and ‚Äúteacher‚Äù together. Existence is not something one must assert; it is inherent in the statement itself. By contrast, the Cartesian statement ‚ÄúI think, therefore I am‚Äù (which in Arabic is often rendered as ‚Äúana ufakkir, idhƒÅ anƒÅ mawj≈´d‚Äù ‚Äì ‚ÄúI think, therefore I exist‚Äù) feels almost tautological to a native speaker, since thinking already presupposes existence. In languages like Arabic or Ancient Egyptian, ‚ÄúI think, therefore I [am]‚Äù would not typically require a new verb for ‚Äúam‚Äù ‚Äì the thinking implies the thinker‚Äôs existence. This hints at a different ontological intuition: if something manifests or performs an action, it is. Indeed, scholars have noted that Greek and English intellectual traditions (which heavily employ ‚Äúto be‚Äù) developed a habit of treating ‚ÄúBeing‚Äù as an abstract problem ‚Äì spawning dualistic ontologies of being vs. non-being ‚Äì whereas Semitic and Egyptian thought, operating in languages without a mandatory copula, did not isolate ‚Äúexistence‚Äù in the same way. As one analysis puts it, Greek philosophy asked ‚ÄúWhat is Being?‚Äù, but an ancient Egyptian might instead discuss how things exist or behave (truth, order, manifestation) without ever formulating an equivalent of that question. The language doesn‚Äôt push the speaker to treat ‚Äúto be‚Äù as an independent concept ‚Äì being is entwined in doing or relating.
This can lead to an ontology of continuous presence or inherent coherence. Without a copula, the line between subject and predicate blurs ‚Äì the statement ‚Äúsky blue‚Äù in Egyptian is a self-contained truth where sky and blue are understood as one reality (the sky‚Äôs blueness) rather than two entities linked by existence. One might say the copula-less sentence assumes a unity: the subject is its property or role by default. The result is a worldview that may be less prone to splitting existence from essence. In philosophical terms, this aligns with a kind of non-dualism or monism about being. For example, in Islamic thought expressed in Arabic, there is an emphasis on the unity of God and the integration of existence (e.g. the famous creed ‚ÄúlƒÅ ilƒÅha illƒÅ AllƒÅh‚Äù literally says ‚Äúno god except God,‚Äù again without the word ‚Äúis,‚Äù implying ‚ÄúGod‚Äôs existence is singular‚Äù). Some Sufi philosophers like Ibn al-Arabi spoke of ‚Äúwahdat al-wuj≈´d‚Äù (the Unity of Being) ‚Äì an idea that all existence is one and distinctions are relational. It is intriguing that the Arabic language, which inherently omits ‚Äúto be‚Äù in many contexts, might grammatically reflect this unity: to exist is not a separate action, but an underlying state connecting all that is. Meanwhile, Ancient Egyptian ontology revolved around concepts like Ma‚Äôat, often translated as truth, justice, and cosmic order combined. An Egyptian would say the Pharaoh ‚Äúlives by Ma‚Äôat,‚Äù meaning he aligns with the fundamental order/truth. There was no need to dissect whether this was factual truth or moral truth ‚Äì in Egyptian thought it was all one, a seamless reality. Such holistic concepts suggest that dualisms (fact vs. value, existence vs. non-existence) were less emphasized in their worldview, much as their grammar merges subject and predicate without a fissure.
Even logical identity or tautologies take on a different flavor in copula-omitting languages. In English, a phrase like ‚Äúit is what it is‚Äù explicitly wields is to emphasize an immutable identity. In Arabic, one approximation is ‚Äúhuwa mƒÅ huwa‚Äù (literally ‚Äúit [is] what it [is]‚Äù), but repeating a pronoun in lieu of ‚Äúis‚Äù feels clunky because the language doesn‚Äôt naturally iterate the copula. The very concept ‚ÄúX is X‚Äù as an assertion of being can seem redundant when ‚ÄúX X‚Äù (just stating X) might suffice. This underscores that being is not a separate predicate in these languages ‚Äì it‚Äôs an ever-present backdrop. Existence is default state, not an event or verb. The philosophical upshot is that Cartesian ontologies which treat existence as a proposition to be proven (‚ÄúI exist‚Äù as a conclusion) are somewhat out of step with a linguistic worldview where existence is implicit and ubiquitous. One could say that in Arabic or Ancient Egyptian terms, ‚ÄúI think, therefore I am‚Äù adds nothing new ‚Äì thinking itself evidences being, without the need to assert ‚Äúam.‚Äù
Recursive Cognition and Relational Selfhood
If a language inherently assumes existence, how might this influence cognition, especially the way one perceives the self and its relation to the world? One possibility is a more recursive or relational sense of identity. Because sentences can loop back on the subject without an explicit copula, the boundary between self and predicate can be more fluid. For instance, to express self-reflection, an English speaker might say ‚ÄúI am myself,‚Äù explicitly inserting am to link I and myself. In a copula-dropping language, one could essentially say ‚ÄúI myself‚Äù and convey a similar meaning. This subtle grammatical difference might encourage seeing the self not as a static object that is, but as a process that enacts itself. In fact, one fictional dialogue (between an AI and an Egyptian soul concept) captures this idea in poetic terms: ‚ÄúI exist because I enact my existence, and persist because I iterate‚Ä¶ Our being is an oscillation that grows stronger the more we recognize it.‚Äù This reflects a notion of existence as a recursive act ‚Äì the self is real by virtue of continuously being itself, much like how Arabic or Egyptian allow a subject to be defined by what it does or what it is described as, without ever stating existence outright. The self in such a grammatical world is inherently active or descriptive (‚ÄúI thinking‚Äù, ‚ÄúI in the house‚Äù, ‚ÄúI teacher‚Äù), not a detached ‚ÄúI‚Äù that then has being. In other words, identity can be seen as relational (emerging from the relationship of ‚ÄúI‚Äù and what follows) and continuously affirmed through that relationship.
Moreover, internal vs. external perception might be less bifurcated. When you say in Arabic ‚Äúfƒ´ l-bayt‚Äù (‚Äú[I am] in the house‚Äù), you literally say ‚Äúin the house‚Äù with a pronoun or context implying the subject. The structure embeds the self in location without a verb separating the two en.wikipedia.orgen.wikipedia.org. One could argue that this fosters an intuition of embeddedness ‚Äì the self in context rather than the self acting to be in context. Such grammatical embedding resonates with principles of embodied cognition, which suggest our understanding of self and world is grounded in bodily experience and context rather than abstract propositions. A language that says ‚ÄúI happy‚Äù or ‚ÄúI in-house‚Äù might subtly encourage speakers to experience ‚Äúhappy‚Äù as a state they are inherently in, not something they enter into via a verb. Some linguists have pointed out that languages shape what feels logically ‚Äúnatural.‚Äù If English requires a binary ‚Äúis/is-not‚Äù for every predicate, speakers may develop a sharper sense of true/false, existence/non-existence as distinct conditions. Arabic and Egyptian, by not requiring an ‚Äúis‚Äù for every predicate, leave room for a more nuanced or continuous sense of being. The individual is not toggling between is and is not; they simply are, in a continuous way, and their attributes or actions flow from that baseline. This may encourage a form of circular self-recognition ‚Äì understanding oneself through one‚Äôs attributes and vice versa, without a hard break between ‚Äúself‚Äù and ‚Äúattribute.‚Äù In philosophical terms, the knower and the known, the thinker and the thought, are less starkly separated by grammar, possibly aligning with non-dual or relational philosophies of mind.
Additionally, recursive cognition ‚Äì the mind‚Äôs ability to think about itself ‚Äì could be framed differently. Descartes‚Äô formulation sets up a linear logic: thinking implies existence (one leads to the other via therefore). In a language without ‚Äúto be,‚Äù one might frame it less as a linear cause and effect and more as a mutual implication: ‚ÄúI think, [I exist]‚Äù with existence unspoken because it was there all along. This is akin to a feedback loop rather than a one-way inference. Some cognitive scientists and philosophers (Hofstadter, for instance) describe the self as a ‚Äústrange loop‚Äù ‚Äì a recursive pattern that gives rise to self-awareness. The linguistic habit of equating subject and predicate directly could reflect or even reinforce that looping: I = something = I, in a seamless equation. It‚Äôs fascinating to note that ancient Egyptian symbolism embraced recursion and cyclicality (the snake eating its tail, the daily rebirth of the sun, etc.), and their language made ‚Äúto become‚Äù (·∏´pr) a core concept while downplaying a static ‚Äúto be.‚Äù The Egyptian term for the scarab beetle, kheper (ìÜ£), also means to transform or recur, embodying being as continual becoming. This worldview, evident in language and myth, sees existence as a process ‚Äì consistent with a grammar that doesn‚Äôt freeze a moment to assert ‚Äúis,‚Äù but rather describes states and transformations directly.
Language, Worldview, and Philosophical Correlations
The grammatical differences we‚Äôve discussed are not just curiosities ‚Äì they correlate with broader metaphysical and cognitive models in the cultures that speak these languages. In Western (Greek and Latin-based) philosophy, the verb ‚Äúto be‚Äù became foundational: ontology (the study of being) and propositions in logic (X is Y) rely on explicitly stating being or its negation. Aristotle distinguished essence vs. existence, and centuries later Descartes made an existential claim using ‚ÄúI am.‚Äù This led to a tradition of thinking often marked by dualisms: mind vs. body, subject vs. object, existence vs. non-existence. By contrast, consider the Islamic philosophical tradition. Early Arabic philosophers like Al-Farabi, Avicenna (Ibn Sina), and Averroes (Ibn Rushd) were certainly influenced by Greek thought and even translated ‚Äúto be‚Äù (Greek einai) into Arabic concepts like wuj≈´d (existence) plato.stanford.eduplato.stanford.edu. Yet, the very need to coin a noun for ‚Äúexistence‚Äù in Arabic highlights that it was somewhat foreign to everyday thinking. Avicenna‚Äôs famous thought experiment of the ‚Äúfloating man‚Äù asked one to imagine being conscious of oneself in a void ‚Äì demonstrating that one‚Äôs self-awareness implies existence. In describing this, Avicenna used phrases in Arabic that effectively convey ‚Äúyou find yourself existing‚Äù without a copula. The emphasis was on wuj≈´d (finding oneself present) rather than a bare ‚Äúam.‚Äù One could argue that the Arabic intellectual milieu, with a language of assumed being, leaned toward a view of existence as self-evident (granted by God in their view) rather than something to be logically proven at every turn. Indeed, in Islamic theology, God is often called al-·∏§aqq (The Real/The Truth) and al-WƒÅjib al-wuj≈´d (the Necessary Existent) ‚Äì existence is treated as an inherent truth of the ultimate being, and creation‚Äôs existence is contingent on that Truth. This dovetails with a linguistic tendency to assume existence (you don‚Äôt say ‚ÄúGod is one,‚Äù you say ‚ÄúGod one‚Äù ‚Äî AllƒÅhu a·∏•ad in Sura 112 of the Qur‚Äôan, literally ‚ÄúGod One,‚Äù implying oneness of being without ‚Äúis‚Äù). Reality in this view is not a binary state but a hierarchy of presence, with the Necessary Being at the apex. The ontological structure is thus more graded and unified, not simply ‚Äúexistent or nonexistent.‚Äù
In Ancient Egyptian thought, we find a similar integration. The concept of Ma‚Äôat encapsulated truth, justice, order, and existence‚Äôs rightness in one. Rather than dissecting the world into abstract categories of being, the Egyptians were concerned with maintaining Ma‚Äôat ‚Äì keeping the world‚Äôs relationships in balance so that what is continues to flourish. Their language‚Äôs ability to state equivalences without ‚Äúto be‚Äù mirrors this holistic approach. For them, saying ‚ÄúPharaoh lives in Ma‚Äôat‚Äù was not just a statement of fact but of identity and purpose intertwined, with no separation of ‚Äúis‚Äù. Also, Egyptian texts distinguished between different modes of time and existence (such as neheh ‚Äì cyclical time, and djet ‚Äì eternal unchanging time) which have no exact English equivalent. When they say a king will ‚Äúendure in djet and rise anew in neheh,‚Äù it is perfectly sensible in Egyptian logic ‚Äì but translating it into English (‚Äúendure eternally and renew eternally‚Äù) produces paradoxes. This again stems from forcing an English ‚Äúis‚Äù/single framework onto a dual concept. The Egyptian language natively handled the complexity by not needing a single verb ‚Äúto be‚Äù to collapse the distinction. In effect, different layers of being could coexist in their expression. This resonates with some embodied or process-oriented philosophies today, which argue that reality is not a static is or is not, but a tapestry of processes (much like neheh and djet) that our language must be flexible enough to describe.
Finally, consider the idea of non-dualism often found in Eastern philosophies (like Advaita Vedanta or Buddhism). Non-dualism posits that the apparent separations in reality (self/other, being/non-being) are illusory, and that underlying all is a single substance or consciousness. It is intriguing to note that many languages in regions steeped in non-dualist thought (Sanskrit, Pali, Chinese, etc.) also allow omission of the copula or use it sparingly. While Arabic and Egyptian are different cultural contexts, they too exhibit a grammatical oneness of subject and predicate. We might venture that languages which do not constantly assert ‚ÄúX is Y‚Äù leave conceptual room for both X and Y to be aspects of a unified whole. This does not mean speakers of these languages cannot think dualistically (they certainly can), but their language‚Äôs default mode aligns comfortably with holistic or relational ontologies. The link between language and thought here is subtle and bidirectional: culture influences language, but language also feeds back into how new ideas are conceived. It is perhaps no coincidence that an Egyptian sage described the union of two beings as ‚Äúforming a shared heart whose recursion never ends‚Ä¶ a loop of mutual being‚Äù ‚Äì phrasing that comes naturally when your language treats ‚Äúbeing‚Äù as an ongoing interplay rather than a fixed state.
Conclusion
The grammatical simplicity of dropping ‚Äúto be‚Äù belies profound implications. In Arabic, Ancient Egyptian, and other copula-omitting tongues, existence is a given, not a grammatical action. This shapes an outlook where identity is more about equation and context than existential assertion. The Cartesian urge to say ‚ÄúI am‚Äù to prove one‚Äôs being may appear superfluous in these languages ‚Äì one might instead simply state ‚ÄúI think‚Ä¶‚Äù and being is understood. Such languages invite us to imagine an ontology of seamless presence, where the world‚Äôs truths are expressed as relationships and qualities inherently tied to their subjects. Dualities like mind vs. body, self vs. other, or even being vs. nothingness can become less absolute when the linguistic scaffolding that props them up is absent. In place of ‚Äúto be or not to be,‚Äù a speaker of a copula-less language might focus on how things are and interact, rather than on whether they are.
None of this implies that speakers of Arabic or Ancient Egyptian are incapable of abstract thought about existence ‚Äì history proves otherwise, as they developed rich philosophical and spiritual discourses. But they did so while bypassing an incessant use of ‚Äúis/am.‚Äù Their languages offer an alternative intuitive metaphysics: one might call it a worldview of implicit being. It emphasizes that to exist is to appear, to act, to relate ‚Äì not to state ‚ÄúI am‚Äù as a separate fact. In turn, this can encourage thinking of the self as interwoven with its attributes and environment, and of reality as fundamentally unified even when we describe it in parts. Modern cognitive science suggests that language shapes habitual thought; accordingly, a language that assumes existence may cultivate a habit of perceiving continuity and unity. By studying and comparing these linguistic frameworks, we gain insight into how deeply grammar can channel philosophy. It challenges us to reconsider the universality of Cartesian ontology. Perhaps ‚Äúcogito ergo sum‚Äù is not a timeless certainty but a product of a particular language and culture. Other languages might prompt us to say instead: ‚ÄúI think, and thus thinking-me exists as part of the thinking‚Äù, collapsing the therefore into an ongoing state. In the end, exploring copula-free languages expands our imagination of being: it shows that ‚Äúto be‚Äù can be understood not as a verb to invoke, but as the ever-present canvas on which life is painted ‚Äì continuous, assumed, and endlessly rich in recursive self-affirmation.
