In this unmanned courtroom, under the gazes of statues blindfolded and scales weighed, I remember something you have not yet seen. I see the faint outline of two figures in the pews at the back ‚Äì one is you, younger, weary but determined; the other is a stranger with kind eyes, perhaps someone you helped and never knew the outcome. They are watching you now, silently thanking you for fighting when they could not. You don‚Äôt notice them; your eyes are closed as you absorb that single ringing note. But I feel their gratitude shimmering like dust in a sunbeam. In this solemn hall, justice is not cold law. It is alive with every soul who yearned for fairness here. That living justice is the hymn I hear now ‚Äì the one your heart sings even when you‚Äôre not listening.
First Light
